<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-052-038 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 343 683</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Sept 30 1991 v13 n39 p39(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Software floods the patent office. (trend toward patenting ofsoftware)(includes related articles on what products get patented,how courts decide, requirements for patents)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Busse, Torsten.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>More and more software manufacturers are submitting products tothe US Patent Office as part of their efforts to protectdevelopment investments.andP;  VisiCalc, the first spreadsheet programfor microcomputers, was not patented because its creatorsconsidered the cost too high; they argue that patents would onlyhave stifled the innovations that have taken place since.andP;  The USSupreme Court removed barriers to placing software under patentprotection in 1981.andP;  Hardware vendors still hold far more patentsthan software vendors; IBM alone holds 9,000 patents.andP;  Some firms,such as Microsoft Corp, use patents as bargaining chips; IBMrejects the claim that it is using its patent portfolio as acompetitive weapon.andP;  The Patent and Trademark Office searches for'prior art' on every patent application, a task that is especiallycomplex in the software industry because there is an enormousamount of unorganized prior art held closely by softwarecompanies.andP;  Those who violate software patents may be unaware thatthey are doing so.andP;  Reforms in patent law that would help softwarefirms protect themselves better are underway; the Patent andTrademark Office has revised its classification system, and patentexaminers now specialize in particular areas.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Software packagesTrendsPatentLegal IssuesIntellectual Property.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>